  "local_port": 40334,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Where can I find a training data set (free or not) for patent/prior art search to train a deep learning engine to select relevant prior art/ patents?",
  "response": "Training a deep learning model for patent and prior art search requires access to comprehensive and well-structured patent datasets. Here are several resources\u2014both free and paid\u2014that you can utilize to obtain such datasets:\n\n### **1. Public Patent Databases**\n\nThese platforms provide extensive patent data which can serve as a foundation for creating your training dataset.\n\n- **United States Patent and Trademark Office (USPTO)**\n  - **Bulk Data Downloads:** The USPTO offers bulk downloads of patent grants and published applications. Data is available in XML format, which includes metadata, abstracts, claims, and full descriptions.\n    - **Link:** [USPTO Bulk Data](https://bulkdata.uspto.gov/)\n  - **Patent Citation Data:** Citations within patents can be used to infer prior art relationships.\n    - **Link:** [USPTO PatentsView](https://www.patentsview.org/download/data/)\n\n- **European Patent Office (EPO)**\n  - **Open Patent Services (OPS):** Provides access to bibliographic, legal status, and full-text patent data.\n    - **Link:** [EPO OPS](https://developers.epo.org/)\n  - **EPO Bulk Data:** Offers bulk downloads for research purposes.\n    - **Link:** [EPO Bulk Data](https://www.epo.org/about-us/open-data/bulk-data.html)\n\n- **Google Patents Public Datasets**\n  - **BigQuery Access:** Google hosts a comprehensive dataset of US patents and published applications on BigQuery, facilitating large-scale analysis.\n    - **Link:** [Google Patents Public Datasets](https://cloud.google.com/bigquery/public-data/patents)\n\n- **PatentsView**\n  - A visualization and analysis tool provided by the USPTO that includes detailed patent data, including citations.\n    - **Link:** [PatentsView](https://www.patentsview.org/)\n\n### **2. Specialized Patent Data Providers**\n\nThese services often offer enhanced data, including enriched metadata, citation networks, and analytics tools, which can be valuable for training models.\n\n- **Lens.org**\n  - **Features:** Combines patent data with scholarly literature and includes citation data. Offers APIs for data access.\n    - **Link:** [The Lens](https://www.lens.org/)\n  - **Data Access:** Free for most uses, with premium options available for advanced features.\n\n- **Derwent Innovation (Clarivate)**\n  - **Features:** Provides curated patent data with enhanced quality, including standardized nomenclature and advanced search capabilities.\n    - **Link:** [Derwent Innovation](https://clarivate.com/products/derwent-innovation/)\n  - **Access:** Subscription-based service.\n\n- **Questel**\n  - **Features:** Offers comprehensive global patent data, including citational analytics and machine translation.\n    - **Link:** [Questel Analytics](https://www.questel.com/)\n  - **Access:** Subscription-based services tailored to different needs.\n\n- **PatentInspiration (Alt Legal)**\n  - **Features:** Provides analytics and search tools for patent data.\n    - **Link:** [PatentInspiration](https://www.altlegal.com/)\n\n### **3. Academic and Research Datasets**\n\nThese datasets are often curated for research purposes and may include labeled data suitable for training machine learning models.\n\n- **Stanford Patent Dataset**\n  - **Description:** Includes machine-translated patents and may have citation information.\n    - **Link:** [Stanford University SNAP Datasets](https://snap.stanford.edu/data/web-graphs.html#StanfordPatents)\n\n- **Patent Citation Network Datasets**\n  - **Description:** Various research projects have compiled citation networks from patent data, which can be useful for understanding prior art relationships.\n    - **Example Link:** [Network Repository - Patent Citation Network](https://networkrepository.com/patent-citation.php)\n\n- **Kaggle Datasets**\n  - **Description:** Kaggle hosts a variety of datasets, including some related to patents and citations.\n    - **Link:** [Kaggle Patent Datasets](https://www.kaggle.com/search?q=patent)\n\n### **4. Commercial APIs and Data Services**\n\nIf you require ready-to-use datasets with additional features like machine-readable labels for prior art relevance, consider commercial APIs.\n\n- **PatSnap**\n  - **Features:** Provides comprehensive patent data, analytics, and machine learning tools.\n    - **Link:** [PatSnap](https://www.patsnap.com/)\n\n- **IP.com**\n  - **Features:** Offers prior art search solutions and patent analytics.\n    - **Link:** [IP.com Prior Art](https://www.ip.com/prior-art)\n\n### **5. Building Your Own Dataset**\n\nIf existing datasets do not fully meet your requirements, you might consider constructing your own:\n\n- **Data Assembly:**\n  - **Patent Documents:** Use sources like USPTO, EPO, or Google Patents to gather patent texts.\n  - **Citations as Labels:** Utilize citation data to establish relationships between patents and their prior art. Citations often indicate relevance, though you may need to refine this for training purposes.\n  - **Text Preprocessing:** Clean and preprocess patent texts to be suitable for deep learning models (e.g., tokenization, embedding).\n\n- **Annotation:**\n  - **Manual Labeling:** For more accurate relationships, consider manually labeling a subset of data or leveraging semi-supervised techniques.\n  - **Expert Review:** Engage patent experts to validate the relevance of prior art selections, enhancing dataset quality.\n\n### **6. Considerations for Using Patent Data**\n\n- **Data Licensing:** Ensure compliance with licensing terms, especially when using commercial datasets or APIs.\n- **Data Volume and Quality:** Patent datasets are typically large; ensure you have the computational resources to handle them. Additionally, data quality (e.g., OCR errors in older patents) can impact model performance.\n- **Natural Language Complexity:** Patents use specialized language and structured sections (abstract, claims, description). Tailor your preprocessing and model architecture to handle this complexity effectively.\n- **Legal Considerations:** Be mindful of using patent data, especially if intending to provide commercial prior art search services, as legal advice and accuracy are critical.\n\n### **7. Additional Resources and Tools**\n\n- **Natural Language Processing Libraries:**\n  - **SpaCy, NLTK, Hugging Face Transformers:** Useful for text preprocessing and building deep learning models.\n  \n- **Machine Learning Platforms:**\n  - **TensorFlow, PyTorch:** Frameworks to develop and train your deep learning models.\n\n- **Data Storage and Management:**\n  - **SQL/NoSQL Databases, Big Data Solutions:** Depending on dataset size and access patterns, choose appropriate storage solutions.\n\n### **Summary**\n\nTo train a deep learning engine for patent/prior art search, leverage a combination of public databases (like USPTO and EPO), specialized data providers (such as The Lens or Derwent Innovation), and possibly commercial APIs for enriched datasets. Depending on your specific requirements, you may need to preprocess and label the data appropriately, potentially combining citation data with manual annotations to improve relevance accuracy. Ensure you comply with data licensing and have the necessary computational resources to handle large-scale patent data.",
